Consider the curve given by

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle y = f(x) = \frac{1}{x^{p}}
\end{align*}

for $\displaystyle 1 \leq x \leq B$ where $\displaystyle p,B$ are
constants with $\displaystyle B > 1$ and $\displaystyle p > 0$.

Refer to parts
{(a)}
and
{(b)}
for the values of A (the area between the curve and the \emph{x}-axis)
and V (the volume obtained by rotating the curve about the
\emph{x}-axis).

(c) Now consider the limit as \emph{B} tends to infinity. For what range
of values of the constant \emph{p} is it true that the volume \emph{V}
has a finite limit while the area \emph{A} becomes infinite? Explain
your answer in terms of your calculations from parts
{(a)}
and
{(b)}
using one sentence.
